## Door Opener Rules

- A door opener assessment uses `assessment_type = 'door_opener'`. The same domain packages run, but only items whose input requirements are satisfied by public data are scored (spec_1 §13.2, lines 1143-1153).
- The applicability matrix is authoritative: exactly 11 items are scorable. Do not score items marked "NOT APPLICABLE" in `Door_Opener_Applicability_Matrix.md`.
- The 11 scorable items span 3 of 12 areas (per `Door_Opener_Applicability_Matrix.md` lines 179-191):
  - Area 2 (Marketing): Online Reputation, Digital/Social Presence, Website Quality
  - Area 4 (Listings): Content Quality, Listing Accuracy
  - Area 11 (Competitive Position): Pricing vs Comps, Amenity Count vs Comps, Reputation Score vs Comps, Resident Services vs Comps, Resident Events vs Comps, Resident Mobile App vs Comps
- Non-applicable areas score as `OUT_OF_SCOPE`, not zero. Coverage metadata must clearly show what was and was not assessed.
- The upgrade path from door opener to full engagement changes `assessment_type` to `full_engagement` and preserves all door opener data. Prior public findings remain comparable — they are not rebuilt from scratch (spec_1 §13.3, lines 1156-1159).

## Public Data Collection Rules

- Door opener data comes from publicly accessible sources only:
  - ILS listings (Apartments.com, Zillow, etc.)
  - Review platforms (Google, Yelp, ApartmentRatings, Facebook)
  - Property website
  - Social media profiles
  - Google Business Profile
  - App stores (resident mobile app)
  - Comp property public data (same sources applied to comp set)
- Data collection sections: Audit Workbook §2 `[DOOR OPENER]` and §10A-10K `[DOOR OPENER]`.
- No PM internal data, CRM data, financial data, work orders, resident interviews, or field validation unless performed publicly or onsite.

## Extension SDK Rules

- New connectors must implement the `VendorAdapter` protocol from `Data_Onramp_Specification.md` (spec_1 §15.1).
- New connectors declare: supported source system type, supported report types, column mappings, adapter class. Validation runs against sample test files.
- New diagnostic packages must provide: metric definitions, benchmark definitions, rule thresholds, impact formulas, output templates (spec_1 §15.2).
- No schema rewrite is required for new packages unless the analysis introduces a truly new fact grain (spec_1 §15.2, line 1217).
- Rubric versions are metadata-driven and deploy independently of core entity tables (spec_1 §15.3). Registration validates weight sums: area weights sum to 100%, item weights sum to 100% per area, sub-item points sum to 100 per checklist item.
- New entity domains register canonical facts in the semantic catalog. Existing workspace, studies, and reporting infrastructure remain reusable (spec_1 §15.4).

## Testing Rules

- Door opener assessment: test that only the 11 applicable items are scored and the remaining 54 return `OUT_OF_SCOPE`.
- Door opener scoring: test that area-level and overall scores are computed correctly using only applicable items.
- Door opener report: test that the door opener report template includes only scored areas and clearly marks non-applicable areas.
- Upgrade to full engagement: test that all door opener data is preserved after upgrade, and that new internal data integrates without rebuilding public findings.
- Connector SDK: test registering a new connector, validating it, and running a sample import through it.
- Package SDK: test registering a new diagnostic package, validating its metrics and formulas, and running it.
- Rubric versioning: test that invalid weight sums (not summing to 100% or 100 points) are rejected at registration.
- All tests use **pytest**. Shared fixtures in `tests/conftest.py`.

## What NOT To Build In This Phase

- Do not modify the core scoring engine — rubric versions extend it, they don't replace it.
- Do not modify the core import pipeline — connectors extend it via the adapter protocol.
- Do not implement AI/ML analysis features — those are outside the current roadmap scope.
